04703nam a22006015i 9780520919686DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19991999cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209196867 a10.1525/97805209196862doi  a(DE-B1597)649113  a(OCoLC)1414457072  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aBL820.C8bR65 1999eb 7aREL0720002bisacsh04a291.2/114/0932211 aRoller, Lynn E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIn Search of God the Mother :bThe Cult of Anatolian Cybele /cLynn E. Roller; ed. by Lynn E. Roller. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1999] 4cÂ©1999  a1 online resource (400 p.) :b76 b/w photographs, 2 line drawings, 2 maps.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Prolegomenon to a Study of the Phrygian Mother Goddess -- tPART 1. THE MOTHER GODDESS IN ANATOLIA -- t2. The Evidence from Prehistory -- t3. The Bronze and Early Iron Ages -- t4. The Cult of the Mother Goddess in Phrygia -- tPART 2. THE MOTHER GODDESS IN GREECE -- t5. The Early Cult -- t6. The Classical Period -- t7. The Hellenistic Period -- tPART 3. FROM CULT TO MYTH -- t8. The Myth of Cybele and Attis -- tPART 4. THE ROMAN MAGNA MATER -- t9. The Arrival of the Magna Mater in Rome -- t10. The Republic and Early Empire -- t11. The Roman Goddess in Asia Minor -- tEpilogue -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book examines one of the most intriguing figures in the religious life of the ancient Mediterranean world, the Phrygian Mother Goddess, known to the Greeks and Romans as Cybele or Magna Mater, the Great Mother. Her cult was particularly prominent in central Anatolia (modern Turkey), and spread from there through the Greek and Roman world. She was an enormously popular figure, attracting devotion from common people and potentates alike. This book is the first comprehensive assembly and discussion of the entire extant evidence concerning the worship of the Phrygian Mother Goddess, from her earliest appearance in the prehistoric record to the early centuries of the Roman Empire.Lynn E. Roller presents and analyzes literary, historiographic, and archaeological data with equal acuity and flair. While previous studies have tended to emphasize the more outrageous aspects of the Mother Goddess's cult, such as her orgiastic rituals and the eunuch priests who attended her, this book places a special focus on Cybele's position in Anatolia and the ways in which the identity of the goddess changed as her cult was transmitted to Greece and Rome. Roller gives a detailed account of the growth, spread, and evolution of her cult, her ceremonies, and her meaning for her adherents.This book will introduce students of Classical antiquity to many aspects of the Great Mother which have been previously unexamined, and will interest anyone who has ever been piqued by curiosity about the Mother Goddess of the ancient Western world.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCybele (Goddess)xCult. 0aGoddessesxMediterranean Region. 0aGoddesseszMediterranean Region. 0aGoddesses. 4aAntiquities & Archaeology. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Antiquities & Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aRoller, Lynn E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021024040uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052091968640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520919686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520919686/original  